body:
My apologies, I created another pull request (https://github.com/apache/incubator-livy/pull/146) and I didn't realize there is this pull request. I'd like to revive this discussion.

I think the primary use case for Livy interactive session is for notebooks (Jupyter/Zeppelin). Data Scientists type code in notebook and view results. Scheduled app submission should use Livy batches instead of sessions.

Livy server garbage collect sessions without "activity" for a period specified by "livy.server.session.timeout", where "activity" is defined as: a) submit statement; b) cancel statement; c) complete statement; d) access REST endpoint sessions/:id/connect;

The strange thing about config "livy.server.session.timeout" is that it simultaneously controls two different things: 1) timeout for idle sessions (timeout since last statement completion time); and 2) max run time for a statement (timeout since last statement submission);

It will eliminate confusion if we only let "livy.server.session.timeout" control timeout for idle sessions, as its name properly suggests. Whether or not we want to provide "livy.server.session.statement.maxruntime" is a different discussion. Note that I'm not aware of a configuration to limit batch job runtime.

@meisam for the scenario you described (thousands of jobs each day by enterprise scheduler), should you use Livy batch job instead of interactive sessions?
